Midterm Project – Cherry Blossom’s First-Blooming Dates in Japan

Yuriko Schumacher

Introduction

Background and purpose of this project

On Tuesday, March 19th, cherry blossoms in the city of Osaka, Japan saw the first blooming – the record earliest. Eleven other Japanese cities recorded its cherry blossoms’ earliest-ever first-blooming this year, and meteorologists say first-bloom dates are getting earlier in recent years in various locations in Japan.

This project aims to illustrate the overall trend of Japanese cherry blossoms’ first-blooming dates and to analyze some of the theories and workings behind the first-bloom dates.

Exploratory data analysis questions

In this project, I’m going to analyze the following questions:

  1. What is an overall trend of Japanese cherry blossom’s first-bloom dates over time? To confirm whether the trend pointed out by meteorologists is true, I’m going to analyze the average first-bloom dates in various locations in Japan over time.

  2. What is the probability of seeing cherry blossoms blooming in the entrance ceremony? In Japan, where the academic year starts in April and ends in March, cherry blossoms are often associated with school’s entrance ceremonies. Whether they can see the cherry blossoms blooming on the ceremony day means a lot to students. I’m going to analyze the first-blooming date to calculate the likelihood of seeing cherry blossoms blooming (at least a little bit) on the entrance ceremony day.

  3. Is 400-degree theory true? What about 600-degree theory? There are several theories about cherry blossom’s first-blooming dates. One of them is the 400-degree theory, which claims the first-blooming happens when the cumulative daily average temperature since February 1st reaches 400 degrees (Celsius). Another is the 600-degree theory. This claims the first-blooming occurs when the cumulative daily high temperature since February 1st reaches 600 degrees (Celsius). I’m going to analyze to see if these theories are correct.

Data

I’m using a data set about cherry blossom’s first-bloom dates since 1953 in dozens of locations in Japan, published by Japan Meteorological Agency. I downloaded a cleaned version posted on Kaggle.com.

This data set includes cherry blossom’s first-blooming dates in more than 100 locations in Japan where the first-blooming were ever observed by Japan Meteorological Agency. For this project, I’m going to focus on 58 locations where they currently conduct observations.

By matching those locations in the data set and their addresses available on the agency’s list of observatories one by one, I confirmed those locations are distributed fairly equally in geographical locations in Japan.

I’m also using data about daily high and average temperature in six major locations in Japan to analyze the third question. Those data sets were directly downloaded from Japan Meteorological Agency, by using the agency’s downloading system.

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)

# load libraries I need
library(tidyverse)
library(moments)
# load cherry blossom's first-blooming data, downloaded from Kaggle
sakura.raw <- read_csv("data/sakura_first_bloom_dates.csv")

# tidy data
sakura.gathered <- sakura.raw %>% 
  select(-`30 Year Average 1981-2010`, -Notes) %>% 
  gather(key = "year", value = "date", "1953":"2020") %>% 
  rename(location = `Site Name`,
         now.observed = `Currently Being Observed`)

# filter out locations currently not observed, calculate date of the year
sakura <- sakura.gathered %>% 
  filter(now.observed == TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(
    date = as.Date(date, format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    date.jan1 = as.Date(paste(year, "-01-01", sep = ""), format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    doy = as.numeric(date - date.jan1)) %>% 
  select(-date.jan1, -now.observed)

head(sakura)

The cleaned data set has 3944 rows and 4 columns. Each row shows an observation, and columns are as follows:

  • location: the location the cherry blossom’s blooming was observed
  • year: the year of observation
  • date: date of first-blooming (Year-Month-Day)
  • doy: date of first-blooming, converted as the number of days after January 1st

I’m computing the dates as number of days after January 1st. About 60 days after January 1st indicates March 1st, about 90 indicates April 1st, and about 120 is May 1st. Negative numbers mean cherry blossoms saw the first-bloom before January 1st that year; in all cases found in this project, they were in late December the year before. I still count those cases as first-blooming in the coming spring (thus negative number of days after January 1st).

For all of the tests in this project, I’m going to apply the alpha value of 0.05.

Qestion 1: Overall trend of first-blooming dates over time

In this section, I’m going to compute the yearly average first-blooming date of all 58 locations from 1953 to 2020.

Plotting all the observed dates and yearly average

First, in order to see the general trend over years, I’m going to plot all the observed first-bloom dates and their yearly average.

# compute yearly average of first-bloom dates
sakura.avg <- sakura %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(avg.doy = mean(doy, na.rm = TRUE))

# plot all observed first-blooming dates 
sakura %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = as.numeric(year))) +
  geom_point(aes(y = doy), color = "#e7298a", alpha = 0.1) +
  geom_line(data = sakura.avg, aes(y = avg.doy)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1955, 1960, 1965, 1970, 1975, 1980, 1985, 1990, 
                                1995, 2000, 2005, 2010, 2015, 2020)) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of cherry blossom's first-bloom days and its average",
       subtitle = "From 1953 to 2020 in 58 locations in Japan",
       x = "Year", y = "Number of days after January 1st") +
  theme_minimal()

In the visualization above, the circles indicate the number of days after January 1st when cherry blossoms saw the first blooming. Overall, the circles are overlapping each other around 75 to 100 days after the new year, meaning mid-March to early-April.

The black line on top of the circles indicates the year’s average. The line suggests the average first-blooming date is slightly becoming earlier over the years. However, this trend is not quite obviously indicated by this visualization.

Plotting 10-year average

Next, I’m going to compute 10-year average of first-blooming date to see if the trend whispered by the visualization above can be confirmed in another way. Here, I’m converting the years to their floor decades (e.g. 1953 to 1950, 2009 to 2000) and calculate the average number of days in each decade.

# compute and plot the 10-year average
sakura %>% 
  mutate(year10 = as.numeric(year) %/% 10 * 10) %>% 
  mutate(year10 = paste(as.character(year10), "s", sep = "")) %>% 
  group_by(year10) %>% 
  summarize(avg.year10 = mean(doy, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year10, y = avg.year10)) +
  geom_line(group = 1) +
  labs(title = "10-year average of cherry blossom's first-bloom date",
       subtitle = "From 1953 to 2020 in 58 locations in Japan",
       x = "Decade", y = "Average number of days after January 1st") +
  theme_minimal()

In the visualization above, the numbers on the “Decade” axis show the 10-year periods starting that year. For example, the point on the line of “1980s” shows the average number of days in all locations from 1980 to 1989. The point on the line of “1950s” only includes the data about the years from 1953 to 1959, while the point on the line of “2020s” only includes the data from the year 2020.

The chart above clearly shows the 10-year average of first-blooming date is constantly getting lower over time, meaning cherry blossoms are blooming earlier and earlier in Japan on average. Comparing to 1960s, they saw the first-blooming about 10 days earlier in 2020.

Analyzing the distribution of dates in 2020

Next, I’m going to look deeper into the distribution of first-blooming dates in a particular year. As an example, I’m analyzing the data from the year 2020.

I’m firstly going to compute the measures of central tendency and variability.

# filter data about the year 2020
sakura.2020 <- sakura %>% 
  filter(year == "2020")

# compute central tendency and variability
mean(sakura.2020$doy) # Mean: 84.93103
## [1] 84.93103
median(sakura.2020$doy) # Median: 84
## [1] 84
sd(sakura.2020$doy) # Standard deviation: 23.77516
## [1] 23.77516
max(sakura.2020$doy) - min(sakura.2020$doy) # Range: 125
## [1] 125

As a result of the computation above, the average first-blooming date in 2020 is about 85 days after January 1st, which is March 26th. The median is 84, meaning March 25th. The standard deviation of the distribution of this data frame is 23.7, and the first-blooming dates ranged 125 days in 2020; the earliest blooming was in Naha, Okinawa on January 6th, while the latest was observed in Wakkanai and Kushiro, both in Hokkaido, on May 10th.

Next, I’m going to plot the distribution and test if it is normally distributed.

# plot distribution
sakura.2020 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = doy)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, fill = "#e7298a", color = "white", alpha = 0.8) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of cherry blossom's first-blooming dates in 2020",
       subtitle = "In 58 locations in Japan",
       x = "Number of days after January 1st", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

From this visualization, I can say this distribution has a single hump and that it looks quite leptokurtic. From the calculation above, mean is slightly larger than the median, suggesting a slight positive skew. However, because of some outliers close to the lower end, the distribution may also look slightly negatively skewed. In any ways, there are so many missing points, especially in the lower half of the distribution, that I can’t quite say if it is skewed in which way.

In order to learn more about this distribution, I’m going to compute its skewness and kurtosis, as well as conduct the Shapiro–Wilk test to test its normality.

# calculate skewness and kurtosis
skewness(sakura.2020$doy) # -0.883243
## [1] -0.883243
kurtosis(sakura.2020$doy) # 5.473665
## [1] 5.473665
# conduct the shapiro-wilk test
shapiro.test(sakura.2020$doy) # p-value = 3.987e-07 ... not normal
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  sakura.2020$doy
## W = 0.8125, p-value = 3.987e-07

First, the skewness is -0.88, indicating a slight negative skew. The kurtosis is 5.47, and it is strongly leptokurtic.

In the Shapiro-Wilk test, the hypotheses are:

  • Null hypothesis: the distribution of number of dates is normally distributed
  • Alternative hypothesis: the distribution of number of dates is not normally distributed

As a result of the test, the p-value is extremely small. Since the alpha level is 0.05, the p-value is below the alpha level. Thus, I reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternative hypothesis; the distribution is not normal.

Question 2: Probability of seeing cherry blossoms in the entrance ceremony day

In this section, I’m going to analyze the probability of seeing cherry blossoms blooming on the date of entrance ceremony. Here, I’m going to focus on a single location: Osaka.

According to Osaka City, most junior-high (middle) schools is going to hold the entrance ceremony on April 3rd, while most elementary school will be holding theirs on April 7th this year. Generally, what’s the probability of cherry blossoms blooming on those days? To answer this question, I’m going to analyze the distribution of first-blooming dates in Osaka.

Distribution of first-blooming dates in Osaka

First, I’m going to filter the data about Osaka and analyze the distribution of its first-blooming date.

# filter data about Osaka
osaka.doy <- sakura %>% 
  filter(location == "Osaka")

# compute central tendency and variability
mean.osaka <- mean(osaka.doy$doy) # 87.47059
median.osaka <- median(osaka.doy$doy) # 87
sd.osaka <- sd(osaka.doy$doy) # 5.041531

# draw histogram for doy distribution
osaka.doy %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = doy)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, fill = "#e7298a", color = "white", alpha = 0.8) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of cherry blossom's first-blooming dates in Osaka",
       subtitle = "From 1953 to 2020",
       x = "Number of days after January 1st", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

# compute skewness and kurtosis
skewness(osaka.doy$doy) # 0.2249174
## [1] 0.2249174
kurtosis(osaka.doy$doy) # 2.648801
## [1] 2.648801
# conduct the Shapiro-Wilk test
shapiro.test(osaka.doy$doy) # p-value = 0.4223
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  osaka.doy$doy
## W = 0.9818, p-value = 0.4223

From the calculation of central tendency, the mean is slightly larger than the median, suggesting a slight positive skew. From the histogram, the distribution looks like to have a single hump (unimodal) and symmetorical.

The skewness is 0.22, confirming the positive skew, but not too far from symmetrical. Kurtosis is 2.65, which is also not too far from 3 (mesokurtic).

In the Shapiro-Wilk test, the hypotheses are:

  • Null hypothesis: the distribution of number of dates is normally distributed
  • Alternative hypothesis: the distribution of number of dates is not normally distributed

The p-value from the Shapiro-Wilk test is p-value = 0.4223, which is above the alpha level of 0.05. Thus, I’m accepting the null hypothesis and conclude it is normally distributed.

Calculating possibility

Next, I’m going to calculate the possibility of seeing cherry blossoms blooming on the date of entrance ceremonies. Here, I’m interpreting the question as “the possibility of having cherry blossom’s first-blooming date BEFORE the date of the entrance ceremony”.

(It is commonly believed that cherry blossoms continue blooming about two weeks after their first blooming. The earliest observed first-blooming date in Osaka is March 20th, so if cherry blossoms started blooming on that day, April 3rd would be exactly two weeks after that, and April 7th would be out of the blooming range. However, for the purpose of this analysis, I’m ignoring the last-blooming date and focusing on whether cherry blossoms at least already had started blooming by the date of entrance ceremonies.)

I’m also not going to take the leap year into consideration. In that case, April 3rd is 92 days, April 7th is 96 days after January 1st. To have cherry blossoms already blooming the day before the date of ceremonies, I need to see if the first-blooming had already occurred one day before the ceremony dates. Since Osaka cherry blossom’s first-blooming dates are normally distributed, I’m going to calculate the z-scores and the probabilities associated with them.

# store entrance ceremony dates
elementary <- 91
middle <- 95

# calculate the z-score for the entrance ceremony dates
z.elementary <- (elementary - mean.osaka) / sd.osaka # 0.7
z.middle <- (middle - mean.osaka) / sd.osaka # 1.49

# calculate the probabilities associated with the z-scores
pnorm(z.elementary) # 0.7580574
## [1] 0.7580574
pnorm(z.middle) # 0.9323439
## [1] 0.9323439

Based on the calculations above, the possibility of having cherry blossoms blooming before the entrance ceremony in elementary schools is 75.8%. The figure for middle schools is 93.2%. In most cases, entrance ceremonies are being held after Osaka saw cherry blossom’s first-blooming.

Question 3: Analysis of 400-degree theory and 600-degree theory

In this section, I’m going to analyze the data set to test if the 400-degree theory and 600-degree theory are true.

  • 400-degree theory: The first-blooming happens when the cumulative daily average temperature since February 1st reaches 400 degrees (Celsius).
  • 600-degree theory: Cherry blossom’s first-blooming occurs when the cumulative daily high temperature since February 1st reaches 600 degrees (Celsius).

In this analysis, I’m focusing on six major cities in Japan: Sapporo, Sendai, Tokyo, Osaka, Fukuoka, and Naha. I chose those cities because those are the places where Japan Meteorological Agency’s Regional Headquarters are located, according to the agency’s list. Additionally, those six cities are fairly equally distributed geologically.

For each location, I obtained the daily average and high temperature from 1953 to 2020. I’m going to identify the date when both theories claim to be the first-blooming date, and compare the date to the actual blooming date for that location every year. I’m then conducting the one-sample t-test to see if the difference between expected first-blooming date and actual date is statistically significant.

# filter the data for six major cities
major.locations <- c("Sapporo", "Sendai", "Tokyo", "Osaka", "Fukuoka", "Naha")
sakura.major <- sakura %>% 
  filter(location %in% major.locations)

1st location: Sapporo

First, I’m going to analyze the data about Sapporo, Hokkaido. I’m going to load the daily temperature data.

# load daily temperature data
sapporo.raw1 <- read_csv("data/daily-temperature/sapporo/1953-1977.csv")
sapporo.raw2 <- read_csv("data/daily-temperature/sapporo/1978-2000.csv")
sapporo.raw3 <- read_csv("data/daily-temperature/sapporo/2001-2020.csv")

# clean data
sapporo.cleaned <- rbind(sapporo.raw1, sapporo.raw2, sapporo.raw3) %>% 
  mutate(date = as.Date(date),
         high.temp = as.numeric(high.temp),
         year = str_sub(date, end = 4),
         month = as.numeric(str_sub(date, start = 6, end = 7))) %>% 
  filter(month != 1) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  mutate(cum.high.temp = cumsum(high.temp),
         cum.avg.temp = cumsum(avg.temp)) 

# identify the first-blooming date claimed by 400-degree theory
sapporo400 <- sapporo.cleaned %>% 
  filter(cum.avg.temp > 400) %>% 
  filter(cum.avg.temp == min(cum.avg.temp)) %>% 
  mutate(
    date.mu = as.Date(date, format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    date.jan1 = as.Date(paste(year, "-01-01", sep = ""), format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    doy.mu = as.numeric(date.mu - date.jan1)) %>% 
  select(date.mu, doy.mu, year)

# identify the first-blooming date claimed by 600-degree theory
sapporo600 <- sapporo.cleaned %>% 
  filter(cum.high.temp > 600) %>% 
  filter(cum.high.temp == min(cum.high.temp)) %>% 
  mutate(
    date.mu = as.Date(date, format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    date.jan1 = as.Date(paste(year, "-01-01", sep = ""), format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    doy.mu = as.numeric(date.mu - date.jan1)) %>% 
  select(date.mu, doy.mu, year)

# merge data with actual first-blooming date and calculate the difference in dates
sapporo400.merged <- sakura.major %>% 
  filter(location == "Sapporo") %>% 
  merge(sapporo400) %>% 
  mutate(diff = doy - doy.mu,
         theory = "400-degree theory") 

sapporo600.merged <- sakura.major %>% 
  filter(location == "Sapporo") %>% 
  merge(sapporo600) %>% 
  mutate(diff = doy - doy.mu,
         theory = "600-degree theory")

Next, I’m going to plot the difference between the actual first-blooming dates and expected first-blooming date.

# draw histogram for difference between actual and expected dates
rbind(sapporo600.merged, sapporo400.merged) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = diff)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype="dotted") +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = theory), color = "white", alpha = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(vars(theory), ncol = 1) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#1b9e77", "#e7298a")) +
  labs(title = "Difference between the actual and expected first-bloom date in Sapporo",
       x = "Difference in days", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

The visualization shows the distribution of difference between the actual first-blooming date and expected first-blooming date based on 400-degree theory (above) and 600-degree theory (below). The dotted line shows the difference of 0 days, which means where the actual date and expected date are the same.

By the visualization above, in every single observed year in Sapporo, cherry blossoms started blooming earlier than the expected date calculated by the 400-degree theory. Likewise, in most observed years in Sapporo, cherry blossoms saw the first-blooming before the expected date based on 600-degree theory as well. Still, the differences between actual and expected dates are relatively smaller in 600-degree theory than 400-degree theory in Sapporo.

Lastly, I’m going to conduct the one-sample t-test for each distribution and the difference between dates are statistically significant.

In this test, the hypotheses are:

  • Null hypothesis: the difference between the actual first-bloom date and the expected first-bloom date based on 400-degree/600-degree theory is 0 days
  • Alternative hypothesis: the difference between the actual first-bloom date and the expected first-bloom date based on 400-degree/600-degree theory is not 0 days
t.test(x = sapporo400.merged$diff, mu = 0) # p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sapporo400.merged$diff
## t = -33.339, df = 66, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -22.08362 -19.58802
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
## -20.83582
t.test(x = sapporo600.merged$diff, mu = 0) # p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sapporo600.merged$diff
## t = -14.19, df = 66, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -6.520719 -4.912117
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
## -5.716418

As shown above, the p-values are both extremely small. Thus in both cases, I reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternative hypothesis, concluding the difference is significant. Thus, in Sapporo, both 400-degree and 600-degree theories don’t hold true.

I’m going to repeat the same analysis for the other five locations.

2nd location: Sendai

# load daily temperature data
sendai.raw1 <- read_csv("data/daily-temperature/sendai/1953-1985.csv")
sendai.raw2 <- read_csv("data/daily-temperature/sendai/1986-2020.csv")

# clean data
sendai.cleaned <- rbind(sendai.raw1, sendai.raw2) %>%

         high.temp = as.numeric(high.temp),
         year = str_sub(date, end = 4),
         month = as.numeric(str_sub(date, start = 6, end = 7))) %>% 
  filter(month != 1) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  mutate(cum.high.temp = cumsum(high.temp),
         cum.avg.temp = cumsum(avg.temp)) 

# identify the first-blooming date claimed by each theory
sendai400 <- sendai.cleaned %>% 
  filter(cum.avg.temp > 400) %>% 
  filter(cum.avg.temp == min(cum.avg.temp)) %>% 
  mutate(
    date.mu = as.Date(date, format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    date.jan1 = as.Date(paste(year, "-01-01", sep = ""), format = "%Y-%m-%d"),

sendai600 <- sendai.cleaned %>% 
  filter(cum.high.temp > 600) %>%

    date.mu = as.Date(date, format = "%Y-%m-%d"),

# merge data with first-blooming date, calculate the difference
sendai400.merged <- sakura.major %>%

sendai600.merged <- sakura.major %>%

# draw histogram
rbind(sendai600.merged, sendai400.merged) %>%

       x = "Difference in days", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

# conduct one-sample t-test
t.test(x = sendai400.merged$diff, mu = 0) # p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sendai400.merged$diff
## t = -31.559, df = 67, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0

##  -11.50808 -10.13898
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
## -10.82353
t.test(x = sendai600.merged$diff, mu = 0) # p-value = 0.5102
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sendai600.merged$diff
## t = -0.66211, df = 67, p-value = 0.5102
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.8855753  0.4443988
## sample estimates:
##  mean of x 
## -0.2205882

In the one-sample t-test above, the null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis are the same as those in Sapporo. They will be the same in other locations as well.

In Sendai, as the result of the t-test the p-value for the difference between actual date and expected date based on 600-degree theory is 0.51, which is above the alpha value of 0.05. Here, I accept the null hypothesis and conclude the difference is 0 days, meaning the actual date and expected date are the same. Thus, in Sendai, the 600-degree theory holds true.

The p-value for the other theory is extremely small, so I accept the alternative hypothesis, concluding the 400-degree theory doesn’t apply here.

3rd location: Tokyo

  filter(month != 1) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>%

# identify the first-blooming date claimed by each theory 
tokyo400 <- tokyo.cleaned %>% 
  filter(cum.avg.temp > 400) %>% 
  filter(cum.avg.temp == min(cum.avg.temp)) %>% 
  mutate(
    date.mu = as.Date(date, format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    date.jan1 = as.Date(paste(year, "-01-01", sep = ""), format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    doy.mu = as.numeric(date.mu - date.jan1)) %>% 
  select(date.mu, doy.mu, year)

tokyo600 <- tokyo.cleaned %>% 
  filter(cum.high.temp > 600) %>% 
  filter(cum.high.temp == min(cum.high.temp)) %>% 
  mutate(
    date.mu = as.Date(date, format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    date.jan1 = as.Date(paste(year, "-01-01", sep = ""), format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    doy.mu = as.numeric(date.mu - date.jan1)) %>% 
  select(date.mu, doy.mu, year)

# merge data with first-blooming date, calculate the difference 
tokyo400.merged <- sakura.major %>% 
  filter(location == "Tokyo") %>% 
  merge(tokyo400) %>% 
  mutate(diff = doy - doy.mu,
         theory = "400-degree theory") 

tokyo600.merged <- sakura.major %>% 
  filter(location == "Tokyo") %>% 
  merge(tokyo600) %>% 
  mutate(diff = doy - doy.mu,
         theory = "600-degree theory")

# draw histogram 
rbind(tokyo600.merged, tokyo400.merged) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = diff)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype="dotted") +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = theory), color = "white", alpha = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(vars(theory), ncol = 1) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#1b9e77", "#e7298a")) +
  labs(title = "Difference between the actual and expected first-bloom date in Tokyo",
       x = "Difference in days", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

# conduct one-sample t-test
t.test(x = tokyo400.merged$diff, mu = 0) # p-value = 0.5568
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  tokyo400.merged$diff
## t = -0.59054, df = 67, p-value = 0.5568
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.9661671  0.5249906
## sample estimates:
##  mean of x 
## -0.2205882
t.test(x = tokyo600.merged$diff, mu = 0) # p-value = 1.519e-07
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  tokyo600.merged$diff
## t = 5.8652, df = 67, p-value = 1.519e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.416385 2.877733
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  2.147059

In Tokyo, the p-value for the difference between actual start date and expected start date based on 400-degree theory is 0.5568, grater than the alpha level of 0.05. Here, I accept the null hypothesis and conclude that difference is 0 days. In Tokyo, 400-degree theory holds true.

The p-value based on 600-degree theory is below the alpha level, so I reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternative hypothesis. In Tokyo, 600-degree theory doesn’t apply.

# merge date difference data from all six locations for both theories
major400 <- rbind(sapporo400.merged,

Based on the t-tests above, the 400-degree theory only holds true in Tokyo, while the 600-degree theory only holds true in Sendai.

However, from the visualization above, also in Osaka and Fukuoka, the distribution of difference in days based on 400-degree theory are concentrated closer to 0 days. Likewise, also in Tokyo, Osaka, and Fukuoka, the distribution of difference in days based on 600-degree theory are concentrated closer to 0 days. In those places, the expected date calculated out of daily temperatures could be one of the indicators to consider cherry blossom’s first-blooming date.

Summary

Findings

Here are the major findings from exploratory data analyses conducted above.

  1. Overall, cherry blossom’s first-blooming date are getting earlier and earlier in Japan. This trend can be more clearly shown by calculating 10-year average first-blooming date and compare the dates over time.

  2. At least in Osaka this year, the probability of holding the elementary school’s entrance ceremony after the cherry blossom’s first-blooming date is quite high (75.8%). The likelihood of having the middle school’s entrance ceremony is even higher (93.2%).

  3. Out of six major cities in Japan (Sapporo, Sendai, Tokyo, Osaka, Fukuoka, and Naha), the 400-degree theory only holds true in Tokyo, and the 600-degree theory only holds true in Sendai. However, in cities like Osaka and Fukuoka, the first-blooming dates identified by those theories could be considered as one of the indicators to expect the first-blooming dates.

Further analysis

  1. For the general trend of first-blooming date, it would be better to analyze if the margin decrease of number of dates until first-blooming is statistically significant.

  2. For the second question, I ignored the effects from the length of cherry blossoms blooming period. The next step would be to calculate the probability of actually being able to see the cherry blossoms blooming, perhaps also considering the full-bloom date. I would be curious to conduct the analysis in different locations in Japan.

  3. For the third question, I could conduct the same analysis for even more locations. Based on the geographical locations, I would be curious to map the area where those theories are true.

Other analysis

  • While in this analysis, I focused on daily high and average temperatures for the 3rd question, meteorologists say the winter temperature also affects the first-blooming date. I would like to conduct a different analysis to see the relationship between the temperature changes in the winter time and the first-blooming date.

  • Based on these analyses, I wonder if I could write an original formula and establish my own theory to expect the first-blooming dates in Japan. I would love to build a website where people can input their location to see the exact expected blooming date.

  • I would be curious to see if those theories would apply in other locations outside of Japan. For example, I would like to know how much the cherry blossoms in Washington DC have the similar characteristics as those in Japan.
